Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

10:10 AM Defendant Jesse L Hansen Schumann in court, in custody.  Attorney Oren Jakobson in court for Jesse L Hansen Schumann.  Attorney Nathan T Oswald in court for State of Wisconsin. 
Attorney Jakobson states that speedy trial was filed on 22CF378 and is set for next week. Due to some issues with witness testimony, he is withdrawing his speedy trial demand and asks that trial be removed from calendar.
Court questions defendant regarding withdrawing speedy trial demand and he wishes to withdraw his request. 
Attorney Lambert makes statement regarding the witness. He thinks there is no new information and there is no new offer. He wants to proceed with trial next week unless defendant wants to accept the offer made.
Attorney Jakobson responds. 
Court grants adjournment and trial will be removed from calendar.
Final pre-trial scheduled for October 27, 2022 at 10:00 am.

records.addlTxt:
5:10 PM Defendant Jesse L Hansen Schumann in court, in custody.  Attorney Oren Jakobson in court for Jesse L Hansen Schumann.  Prosecuting attorney Nathan T. Oswald in court for the State of Wisconsin. 
Jesse Nehls is sworn as a witness and questioned by Attorney Oswald. He is a deputy with the Wood County Sheriff's Department. On 8/6/22, he was dispatched to a campground location regarding a disturbance. M.L.K. indicated that defendant came to her campsite and spent the night. They got into an argument the next morning. They located defendant at a bar in Arpin. The witness identifies the defendant in the courtroom.  Defendant admitted that he was at the campground but was with the occupants of the campsite next to MLK. Attorney Jakobson cross-examines witness.  Attorney Oswald asks Court to take judicial notice of 3 Wood County cases where defendant was out on bond for and is to have no contact with alleged victim. Court takes judicial notice.
Court finds probable cause that a felony was committed and the defendant committed it. Not guilty plea to all counts. Attorney Jakobson requests that bond be modified to $500 cash. State is opposed. Attorney Jakobson makes additional statement. Court denies motion to modify bond. Attorney Jakobson states that he will be filing a speedy trial demand.
Final pre-trial scheduled for October 7, 2022 at 10:00 am.
